[The summary of the referenced journal article is extracted below:

Summary
-------
"Background
Zoonotic tuberculosis is defined as human infection with _Mycobacterium bovis_. Although globally, India has the largest number of human tuberculosis cases and the largest cattle population, in which bovine tuberculosis is endemic, the burden of zoonotic tuberculosis is unknown. The aim of this study was to obtain estimates of the human prevalence of animal-associated members of the _Mycobacterium tuberculosis_ complex (MTBC) at a large referral hospital in India.

"Methods
We did a molecular epidemiological surveillance study of 940 positive mycobacteria growth indicator tube (MGIT) cultures, collected from patients visiting the outpatient department at Christian Medical College (Vellore, India) with suspected tuberculosis between [1 Oct 2018, and 31 Mar 2019]. A PCR-based approach was applied to subspeciate cultures. Isolates identified as MTBC other than _M. tuberculosis_ or as inconclusive on PCR were subject to whole-genome sequencing (WGS), and phylogenetically compared with publicly available MTBC sequences from south Asia. Sequences from WGS were deposited in the National Center for Biotechnology Information Sequence Read Archive, accession number SRP226525 (BioProject database number PRJNA575883).

"Findings
The 940 MGIT cultures were from 548 pulmonary and 392 extrapulmonary samples. A conclusive identification was obtained for all 940 isolates; wild-type _M. bovis_ was not identified. The isolates consisted of _M. tuberculosis_ (913 [97.1%] isolates), _M. orygis_ (7 [0.7%]), _M. bovis_ BCG (5 [0.5%]), and non-tuberculous mycobacteria (15 [1.6%]). Subspecies were assigned for 25 isolates by WGS, which were analysed against 715 MTBC sequences from south Asia. Among the 715 genomes, no _M. bovis_ was identified. Four isolates of cattle origin were dispersed among human sequences within _M. tuberculosis_ lineage 1, and the seven _M. orygis_ isolates from human MGIT cultures were dispersed among sequences from cattle.

"Interpretation
_M. bovis_ prevalence in humans is an inadequate proxy of zoonotic tuberculosis. The recovery of _M. orygis_ from humans highlights the need to use a broadened definition, including MTBC subspecies such as _M. orygis_, to investigate zoonotic tuberculosis. The identification of _M. tuberculosis_ in cattle also reinforces the need for One Health investigations in countries with endemic bovine tuberculosis."

Although human TB is usually caused by _Mycobacterium tuberculosis_, other species within MTBC can also cause TB in humans. MTBC is composed of genetically related species that include _M. tuberculosis_, _M. bovis_ (the usual cause of bovine tuberculosis), _M. bovis_-BCG, _M. microti_ (a pathogen in rodents), _M. caprae_ (a pathogen in multiple mammalian species), _M. pinnipedii_ (a pathogen primarily in seals), _M. mungi_ (a pathogen in banded mongooses), and _M. canettii_ and _M. africanum_ (both cause human TB in Africa). There are 2 additional members of MTBC, _M. dassie_ (a pathogen of hyrax, aka dassie, a small, herbivorous mammal) and _M. orygis_. _M. orygis_ was initially isolated from 11 animals (a cow and a rhesus monkey from South Asia, and waterbuck, deer, and antelope, including oryx, in zoos), and 11 humans (9 from South Asia) (1). _M. orygis_ has also been isolated from dairy cattle in Chennai, India (2), and wild animals in Nepal (3).

In 2016, WHO estimated that there were 147 000 new cases of zoonotic TB in people and 12 500 deaths due to the disease (4). Zoonotic TB in humans is thought to be predominantly caused by _M. bovis_, but members of MTBC other than _M. bovis_ can be zoonotic pathogens. In the study referenced in the news report above, _M. orygis_ was isolated from less than 1% of patients with suspected TB in Vellore, India, but no _M. bovis_ was identified. _M. orygis_ has been reported to have caused lymphadenitis in a patient in the USA who was born in Pakistan and lived in India prior to emigrating to the USA (5). _M. orygis_ has also been reported to have been transmitted to a dairy cow in New Zealand from a tuberculosis patient, who was born and lived in India until emigrating to New Zealand (6).

Vellore is a city with a population of 138 803 residents in 2011 in the state of Tamil Nadu, in southern India. Vellore is 138km (86 mi) west of the coastal city of Chennai. A map showing the location of Vellore can be found at https://www.google.com/maps/dir/Chennai,+Tamil+Nadu,+India/Vellore,+Tamil+Nadu,+India.

References
